<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{uchini}}}} expresses the general time in which a state or action occurs.
</p>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{uchini}}}} can be preceded by a verb describing a state.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{rain}}ga@KJ{{descend}}ranai@EM{{uchini}}@KT{{tenisu}}woshitekimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I'll go and play tennis (and come back) before it rains.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{uchini}}}} can be preceded by a verb describing a progressive action.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{consider}}eteiru@EM{{uchini}}@KJ{{part}}karanakunatta}}.
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      While thinking about it, I got lost.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{uchini}}}} can be preceded by an adjective expressing a duration.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{warm}}kai@EM{{uchini}}@KJ{{drink}}de kudasai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Please drink it while it is warm.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{uchini}}}} can be preceded by an noun expressing a duration.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{rest}}mino@EM{{uchini}}yoku@KJ{{sleep}}teokimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I'll sleep a lot during the holiday.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
The @HI{{@EM{{uchini}}}} clause may express a time limit beyond which an action will become difficult.
The meaning in this case is "do something before the situation changes".
The main clause should express a volitional action.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{day^book}}niiru@EM{{uchini}}@FG{{@KJ{{one^degrees}}:ichido}}@FG{{@KJ{{wealth^gentleman^mountain}}:fujisan}}ni@FG{{@KJ{{ascend}}:no}}bottemitai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      While I'm in Japan I'd like to have a go at climbing Mt. Fuji.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{uchini}}}} may indicate a time during which a change becomes apparent. In this latter case the following clause should not express intention
or volition. The meaning here is that while the state expressed by the @HI{{@EM{{uchini}}}} clause continues, the action or state expressed by the
main clause happens at the same time.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{sound^music}}:ongaku}}wo@FG{{@KJ{{hear}}:ki}}iteiru@EM{{uchini}}@FG{{@KJ{{sleep}}:nemu}}tteshimatta.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      While listening to the music, I fell asleep.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
The expression before @HI{{@EM{{uchini}}}} is always non-past even if the sentence itself is in the past.
</p>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{uchini}}}} cannot be used where the noun used is an event such as a class, a conference or a game.
</p>

